1
00:00:04,440 --> 00:00:09,179
The bar charts you saw in the previous concept were all encoded with

2
00:00:09,179 --> 00:00:13,779
the absolute frequency or number of data points on the length axis.

3
00:00:13,779 --> 00:00:15,984
However, in some cases,

4
00:00:15,984 --> 00:00:17,460
you might instead be interested in

5
00:00:17,460 --> 00:00:22,450
the relative frequency or what proportion of the data falls in each category.

6
00:00:22,449 --> 00:00:28,589
For example; Let's say that we have daily air quality data from three cities for a year.

7
00:00:28,589 --> 00:00:31,390
If we are interested in estimating the proportion of

8
00:00:31,390 --> 00:00:34,234
days that saw good air quality from our plot,

9
00:00:34,234 --> 00:00:39,649
then trying to do this from the plot of counts require us to do some estimation work.

10
00:00:39,649 --> 00:00:43,310
We would need to estimate the relative area of the Good bar to

11
00:00:43,310 --> 00:00:47,895
all the bars together or have to do some mental calculations of some.

12
00:00:47,895 --> 00:00:51,609
Changing the Count axis to relative proportions makes it

13
00:00:51,609 --> 00:00:56,024
much easier to see how much each category contributes to the whole.

14
00:00:56,024 --> 00:00:59,710
We can just read the height of the Good bar on the vertical axis and

15
00:00:59,710 --> 00:01:03,799
find that almost 70 percent of days had good air quality.

